detaileddescription.para: Close a previously declared nested namespace. Tokens should be passed to this macro in the reverse order they were declared in (not actually necessary for valid code, but it is more self documentating to do so).

Callback macro for recursive macro expansion for nested namespace end pasting. ns is the namespace to paste. Note that it is not strictly necessary to pass the namespace name to this macro, as it only pastes a single bracket; it is more self documenting to do so, however.
Declare a nested namespace, with each successive token in the comma-separated argument list being declared inside the namespace of the previous token.
Callback macro for recursive macro expansion for nested namespace start pasting. ns is the namespace to paste.
Mark a function result as no-discard, so that a compiler warning is issued if this happens.

Expose a pointer reference for an instance member Member named Func. The variable argument list is to allow specification of 'const' as part of the function return type. This is the non-const member function version.
Expose a pointer reference for an instance member Member named Func. This is the const member function version.

Initialize a member of a struct which is not POD using the dot ('.') initializer syntax. GCC and clang handle this for things using std::bind/member function pointers, but the Intel compiler does not. Using the dot syntax is nice, because if you have multiple members of the same type in the same struct, the intent of the programmer is clear.
Alias for RCSW_WARNING_DISABLE, a compiler-agnostic way to ignore compiler warnings within a given diagnostic context.
Alias for RCSW_WARNING_DISABLE_POP, a compiler-agnostic way to pop warning ignores from the stack.
Very useful for disabling warnings from headers/frameworks which you have no control over.
Alias for RCSW_WARNING_DISABLE_PUSH, a compiler-agnostic way to push warning ignores onto the stack.
Very useful for disabling warnings from headers/frameworks which you have no control over.

Readability-enhancing macro for declaring that you are wrapping a function provided by a member variable/parent class/etc. You don't HAVE to use this macro, but doing so generally saves some typing, and makes your code more self-documenting.
The variable argument list is to allow specification of 'const' as part of the function declaration.

Declare a "simple" overrnide of an inherited function with the pure attribute. Should be NOT be used if the override is complex to implement (i.e. for every instance of this macro in a header file there should be an instance of RCPPSW_WRAP_DEF_OVERRIDE() in the corresponding source file for a class).

Wrap a public function, member variable (can't be a pointer type), or even another member function that returns an object that contains the function you want to wrap). The variable argument list is to allow specification of 'const' as part of the function definition. Wrapped functions can take any number of arguments of any type.
Cannot be used to wrap overriden functions.

memberdef.name: RCPPSW_WRAP_DECLDEF_AS
memberdef.initializer: template <typename... Args> \ auto NewName(Args&&... args) \ __VA_ARGS__->decltype(std::declval<decltype(Callable)>().Func(args...)) { \ return (Callable).Func(std::forward<Args>(args)...); \ }

detaileddescription.para: Same as RCPPSW_WRAP_DECLDEF, but renames the function wrapper.

Wrap a public function from a member variable (or even another member function that returns an object that contains the function you want to wrap). The variable argument list is to allow specification of 'const' as part of the function definition. Wrapped functions must take 0 arguments (can't do anything other than that for a general macro that works with virtual functions).
Should be used to wrap overriden functions in the current class (e.g the enclosing class implements the same interface as a member variable).

Readability-enhancing macro for defining the body of a function which wraps Func provided by Handle. You don't HAVE to use this macro, but doing so generally saves some typing, and makes your code more self-documenting.
The variable argument list is to allow specification of 'const' as part of the function definition.
Define a "simple" override of an inherited function with the pure attribute in which the corresponding function on the handle is called and the result returned.

memberdef.name: RCPPSW_WRAP_DEFP
memberdef.initializer: auto Class::Func(void) \ __VA_ARGS__->decltype(std::declval<decltype(*Handle)>().Func()) { \ if (nullptr == Handle) { \ return NullRet; \ } \ return (Handle)->Func(); \ }

detaileddescription.para: Same as RCPPSW_WRAP_DEF, but for Handle instances which are pointers. Requires an additional specification of what to return if the Handle is NULL.
Same as RCPPSW_WRAP_DEF_OVERRIDE, but for Handle instances which are pointers. Requires an additional specification of what to return if the Handle is NULL.
